<paragraph id="8BC336E9D20C9D213AD4DAF7EC15FC10" blockId="25.[136,1452,975,1974]" box="[136,613,975,1002]" pageId="25" pageNumber="160">Dimensions: L: 88–96 µm, Td: 57–68 µm.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC336E9D20C9D213AE1DACBEAD2FBAF" blockId="25.[136,1452,975,1974]" pageId="25" pageNumber="160">
Cell shape: Pentagonal cells, dorsoventrally compressed (
<figureCitation id="13472A6CD20C9D21396EDACBEDE9FBF7" box="[818,921,1011,1037]" captionStart="FIGURE 17" captionStartId="26.[136,229,2028,2050]" captionTargetBox="[235,1353,190,2004]" captionTargetId="figure-19@26.[235,1353,190,2004]" captionTargetPageId="26" captionText="FIGURE 17. Peridinium limbatum. A. Ventral view. B. Dorsal view. C. Sulcal plates. D. Sa: anterior sulcal plate. E. Sp: posterior sulcal plate. F. Theca: ventral view. G. Theca: dorsal view. Bar in A, B=10µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5426121" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5426121/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="160">Fig. 17A</figureCitation>
).Triangular epitheca, longer than the hypotheca, with left bended apex (
<figureCitation id="13472A6CD20C9D213BD3DD2FEF87FBCB" box="[399,503,1047,1073]" captionStart="FIGURE 17" captionStartId="26.[136,229,2028,2050]" captionTargetBox="[235,1353,190,2004]" captionTargetId="figure-19@26.[235,1353,190,2004]" captionTargetPageId="26" captionText="FIGURE 17. Peridinium limbatum. A. Ventral view. B. Dorsal view. C. Sulcal plates. D. Sa: anterior sulcal plate. E. Sp: posterior sulcal plate. F. Theca: ventral view. G. Theca: dorsal view. Bar in A, B=10µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5426121" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5426121/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="160">Fig. 17B</figureCitation>
). The hypotheca has short antapical horns separated by an antapical concavity. The cingulum descending, being its ends displaced no longer than one cingular height (
<figureCitation id="13472A6CD20C9D213E7BDD03EAE5FBAF" box="[1063,1173,1083,1109]" captionStart="FIGURE 17" captionStartId="26.[136,229,2028,2050]" captionTargetBox="[235,1353,190,2004]" captionTargetId="figure-19@26.[235,1353,190,2004]" captionTargetPageId="26" captionText="FIGURE 17. Peridinium limbatum. A. Ventral view. B. Dorsal view. C. Sulcal plates. D. Sa: anterior sulcal plate. E. Sp: posterior sulcal plate. F. Theca: ventral view. G. Theca: dorsal view. Bar in A, B=10µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5426121" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5426121/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="160">Figs. 17F</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC336E9D20C9D213AE1DD67EC76FAF3" blockId="25.[136,1452,975,1974]" pageId="25" pageNumber="160">
Thecal characteristics: Tabulation, Po,4ʹ, 3a, 7ʹʹ, 5c, 5s, 5ʹʹʹ, 2ʹʹʹʹ. The Po is surrounded by raised rim formed by the edges of the apical plates. Plate 1ʹ is big and extends in the short apical horn curved to the left (
<figureCitation id="13472A6CD20C9D213EFADDBBEB79FB67" box="[1190,1289,1155,1181]" captionStart="FIGURE 17" captionStartId="26.[136,229,2028,2050]" captionTargetBox="[235,1353,190,2004]" captionTargetId="figure-19@26.[235,1353,190,2004]" captionTargetPageId="26" captionText="FIGURE 17. Peridinium limbatum. A. Ventral view. B. Dorsal view. C. Sulcal plates. D. Sa: anterior sulcal plate. E. Sp: posterior sulcal plate. F. Theca: ventral view. G. Theca: dorsal view. Bar in A, B=10µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5426121" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5426121/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="160">Fig. 17F</figureCitation>
). The 2ʹ and 4ʹ plates are elongated. The plate 2a is hexagonal, big, and located just above of the 4ʹʹ (
<figureCitation id="13472A6CD20C9D213E1CDD9FEAD8FB3B" box="[1088,1192,1191,1217]" captionStart="FIGURE 17" captionStartId="26.[136,229,2028,2050]" captionTargetBox="[235,1353,190,2004]" captionTargetId="figure-19@26.[235,1353,190,2004]" captionTargetPageId="26" captionText="FIGURE 17. Peridinium limbatum. A. Ventral view. B. Dorsal view. C. Sulcal plates. D. Sa: anterior sulcal plate. E. Sp: posterior sulcal plate. F. Theca: ventral view. G. Theca: dorsal view. Bar in A, B=10µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5426121" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5426121/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="160">Fig. 17G</figureCitation>
). Plate 7ʹʹ is wider than the 1ʹʹ. Hypotheca has two small appendices formed by the 1ʹʹʹ and 1ʹʹʹʹ, 5ʹʹʹ and 2ʹʹʹʹ plates (fig. 17G and 14F) with a small pair of spines at their edges.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC336E9D20C9D213AE1DC2BECA1FA47" blockId="25.[136,1452,975,1974]" pageId="25" pageNumber="160">
Cingulum and sulcus: Narrow, descendant cingulum formed by 5 plates. Narrow sulcus, formed by 6 plates, penetrates slightly into the epitheca, and widens toward the antapex. The plate Sa is typical of the genus with a long body that slightly penetrates the epitheca and a lobe on its left side (
<figureCitation id="13472A6CD20C9D2139D7DC63EA16FA8F" box="[907,1126,1371,1397]" captionStart="FIGURE 17" captionStartId="26.[136,229,2028,2050]" captionTargetBox="[235,1353,190,2004]" captionTargetId="figure-19@26.[235,1353,190,2004]" captionTargetPageId="26" captionText="FIGURE 17. Peridinium limbatum. A. Ventral view. B. Dorsal view. C. Sulcal plates. D. Sa: anterior sulcal plate. E. Sp: posterior sulcal plate. F. Theca: ventral view. G. Theca: dorsal view. Bar in A, B=10µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5426121" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5426121/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="160">Figs. 17C and 17D</figureCitation>
). The plate Sp is shaped like an isosceles triangle, laterally extended with its posterior margin concave and the left margin with a strong U-notch, corresponding to the insertion of the Spa (
<figureCitation id="13472A6CD20C9D213803DC9BECB4FA47" box="[607,708,1443,1469]" captionStart="FIGURE 17" captionStartId="26.[136,229,2028,2050]" captionTargetBox="[235,1353,190,2004]" captionTargetId="figure-19@26.[235,1353,190,2004]" captionTargetPageId="26" captionText="FIGURE 17. Peridinium limbatum. A. Ventral view. B. Dorsal view. C. Sulcal plates. D. Sa: anterior sulcal plate. E. Sp: posterior sulcal plate. F. Theca: ventral view. G. Theca: dorsal view. Bar in A, B=10µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5426121" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5426121/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="160">Fig. 17E</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC336E9D20C9D213AE1DCFFEF0CF9B7" blockId="25.[136,1452,975,1974]" pageId="25" pageNumber="160">
Ornamentation: The surface ornamentation of the main plates is a relief reticulum formed by solid cords and nodules with 1-3 pores in each alveolus and presence of intercalary bands. Tabular margins bordered by well-marked marginal ridges. Lists, with radial ribs, rise from the margins of the cingulum and from the lateral sutures along the apical horn. (
<figureCitation id="13472A6CD20C9D213B40DF0BEF1FF9B7" box="[284,367,1587,1613]" captionStart="FIGURE 17" captionStartId="26.[136,229,2028,2050]" captionTargetBox="[235,1353,190,2004]" captionTargetId="figure-19@26.[235,1353,190,2004]" captionTargetPageId="26" captionText="FIGURE 17. Peridinium limbatum. A. Ventral view. B. Dorsal view. C. Sulcal plates. D. Sa: anterior sulcal plate. E. Sp: posterior sulcal plate. F. Theca: ventral view. G. Theca: dorsal view. Bar in A, B=10µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5426121" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5426121/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="160">Fig. 17</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC336E9D20C9D213AE1DF6FEAD7F98B" blockId="25.[136,1452,975,1974]" box="[189,1191,1623,1650]" pageId="25" pageNumber="160">
Locality: Chuza reservoir in Central 
<collectingCountry id="F36B7679D20C9D213805DF6FECBAF98B" box="[601,714,1623,1649]" name="Colombia" pageId="25" pageNumber="160">Colombia</collectingCountry>
, deposited in Dr. Boltovskoy´s Collection.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC336E9D20C9D213AE1DF43EA20F8DF" blockId="25.[136,1452,975,1974]" pageId="25" pageNumber="160">
Comments: this is a big and easily identified species due to its particular shape and it agree with the description by (
<bibRefCitation id="EFED4B18D20C9D213ACCDFA7EF50F943" author="Stokes, A. C." box="[144,288,1695,1721]" pageId="25" pageNumber="160" pagination="244 - 255" refId="ref16583" refString="Stokes, A. C. (1887) Notices of new fresh-water infusoria. Proceedings of the American Philosophical Society 24: 244 - 255." type="journal article" year="1887">Stokes 1887</bibRefCitation>
). Our measures are similar to those given by 
<bibRefCitation id="EFED4B18D20C9D213942DF98EA3FF943" author="Moestrup, O. &amp; Calado, A. J." box="[798,1103,1695,1722]" pageId="25" pageNumber="160" refId="ref16007" refString="Moestrup, O. &amp; Calado, A. J. (2018) Susswasserflora von Mitteleuropa. 6. Dinophyceae. B. Budel, G. Gartner, L. Krienitz &amp; M. Schagerl (Eds.) Springer, Berlin, 561 pp. https: // doi. org / 10.1007 / 978 - 3 - 662 - 56269 - 7 _ 7" type="book" year="2018">Moestrup &amp; Calado (2018)</bibRefCitation>
and bigger than those in 
<bibRefCitation id="EFED4B18D20C9D213F31DFA7EEA6F927" author="Carty, S." pageId="25" pageNumber="160" refId="ref14134" refString="Carty, S. (2014) Freshwater Dinoflagellates of North America. Cornell University Press, New York, 272 pp. https: // doi. org / 10.7591 / 9780801470370" type="book" year="2014">Carty (2014)</bibRefCitation>
. In our specimens, the plate 2a looks triangular, because three of its sides are very short, especially the one that borders 3ʹ plate (
<figureCitation id="13472A6CD20C9D213B1EDFDFEFD9F8FB" box="[322,425,1767,1793]" captionStart="FIGURE 17" captionStartId="26.[136,229,2028,2050]" captionTargetBox="[235,1353,190,2004]" captionTargetId="figure-19@26.[235,1353,190,2004]" captionTargetPageId="26" captionText="FIGURE 17. Peridinium limbatum. A. Ventral view. B. Dorsal view. C. Sulcal plates. D. Sa: anterior sulcal plate. E. Sp: posterior sulcal plate. F. Theca: ventral view. G. Theca: dorsal view. Bar in A, B=10µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5426121" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5426121/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="160">Fig. 17G</figureCitation>
). On the first sulcal description by 
<bibRefCitation id="EFED4B18D20C9D213971DFDFEA7AF8F8" author="Evitt, W. R. &amp; Wall, D." box="[813,1034,1767,1794]" pageId="25" pageNumber="160" pagination="1 - 23" refId="ref14761" refString="Evitt, W. R. &amp; Wall, D. (1968) Dinoflagellate studies IV. Theca and cyst of recent freshwater Peridinium limbatum (Stokes) Lemmermann. Stanford University Publication. Geological Sciences 12: 1 - 23." type="journal article" year="1968">Evitt &amp; Wall (1968)</bibRefCitation>
they show six sulcal plates, however, in our samples the Sm plate was not observed, due to its small size it can often be lost.
</paragraph>
